      "text": {
        "*": "<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Problem\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Problem</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Solutions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Solutions</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Solution_1\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Solution 1</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Solution_2\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Solution 2</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Resources\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Resources</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Problem\">Problem</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/wiki/index.php?title=2003_Polish_Mathematical_Olympiad_Problems/Problem_3&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Problem\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Find all <a href=\"/wiki/index.php/Polynomial\" title=\"Polynomial\">polynomials</a> <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/0/c/10cb764f88509fb1c8012366993fdbee98f31bc5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W$\" style=\"vertical-align: -1px\" width=\"22\" height=\"14\" /> with <a href=\"/wiki/index.php/Integer\" title=\"Integer\">integer</a> <a href=\"/wiki/index.php/Coefficient\" title=\"Coefficient\">coefficients</a> satisfying the following condition: for every <a href=\"/wiki/index.php/Natural_number\" title=\"Natural number\">natural number</a> <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/7/4/174fadd07fd54c9afe288e96558c92e0c1da733a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n$\" width=\"10\" height=\"8\" />, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/b/0/4b063495d0243e7bc52c3a7f231362bdc4a03775.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^n-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"48\" height=\"13\" /> is divisible by <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/9/8/7987ffa8a557c433381a8250fa991b77298ce1b5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n)$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"43\" height=\"18\" />.\n</p><p><i>Note: The expression \"natural number\" is ambiguous, but this is irrelevant, as every integer is a divisor of <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/8/2/d/82dfea9ab7fc55c66a3c9b6e3ab99b5aa1bd4b4e.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^0 -1 = 0$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"80\" height=\"15\" />.</i>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Solutions\">Solutions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/wiki/index.php?title=2003_Polish_Mathematical_Olympiad_Problems/Problem_3&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Solutions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The only solutions are <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/7/f/27ffdf54dc81864d8e487dfcdcabe8c4aa7e834f.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W=1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"52\" height=\"13\" /> and <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/e/1/1e14eed668b193e7742ed922a88a45c99f3ba285.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W=-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"66\" height=\"13\" />.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Solution_1\">Solution 1</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/wiki/index.php?title=2003_Polish_Mathematical_Olympiad_Problems/Problem_3&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Solution 1\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Suppose that for some <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/7/4/174fadd07fd54c9afe288e96558c92e0c1da733a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n$\" width=\"10\" height=\"8\" />, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/6/3/0/630a93d75b4e9bdbaf82e20d01fca1e5074f4104.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n) \\neq \\pm 1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"91\" height=\"18\" />.  Then <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/9/8/7987ffa8a557c433381a8250fa991b77298ce1b5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n)$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"43\" height=\"18\" /> has a prime divisor <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/0/6/1/0615acc3725de21025457e7d6f7694dab8e2f758.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"8\" height=\"11\" /> which divides <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/b/0/4b063495d0243e7bc52c3a7f231362bdc4a03775.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^n-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"48\" height=\"13\" />.  (In particular, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/0/6/1/0615acc3725de21025457e7d6f7694dab8e2f758.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"8\" height=\"11\" /> is odd.)  Evidently, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/6/c/5/6c5adf1ec539b26cf1215decc98e8cebbb03eaac.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n+q) \\equiv W(n) \\equiv 0 \\pmod{q}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"248\" height=\"18\" />, so <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/0/6/1/0615acc3725de21025457e7d6f7694dab8e2f758.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"8\" height=\"11\" /> also divides <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/0/a/1/0a1f3ffda4a115b60e58dc38b351e49529f02072.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n+q)$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"74\" height=\"18\" />, which divides <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/5/7/9577491396d56cdf8db5697c7154e32f499ea6ff.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^{n+q}-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"65\" height=\"15\" />.  Thus <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/d/a/0/da0affebf24668767e4847d900b2e221284660e4.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^{n+q} \\equiv 1 \\equiv 2^n \\pmod{q}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"181\" height=\"19\" />.  Since <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/0/6/1/0615acc3725de21025457e7d6f7694dab8e2f758.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"8\" height=\"11\" /> is an odd prime, we may divide by <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/6/c/3/6c36f0b157e8c2fbe0638c2f2b378e08d07695aa.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^n$\" width=\"17\" height=\"12\" /> to obtain <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/5/8/6/58698896c057425aca38e49bb101920a062917db.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^q \\equiv 1 \\pmod{q}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"120\" height=\"18\" />.  But by <a href=\"/wiki/index.php/Fermat%27s_Little_Theorem\" title=\"Fermat&#39;s Little Theorem\">Fermat's Little Theorem</a>, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/b/4/4/b440b063f3a90b2b5a8f40fd2323cb25619820e4.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^q \\equiv 2 \\pmod{q}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"120\" height=\"18\" />, so <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/d/a/7/da7a705a676fa68cf2165d5b1b0119a071bf17c7.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{q}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"113\" height=\"18\" />, a contradiction.\n</p><p>Thus <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/f/0/e/f0edfdfea723a2972160f244747e9f0d1c1aece1.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n) = \\pm 1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"91\" height=\"18\" />, for all <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/7/4/174fadd07fd54c9afe288e96558c92e0c1da733a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n$\" width=\"10\" height=\"8\" />.  Since all polynomials bounded over the integers are constant, it follows that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/7/f/27ffdf54dc81864d8e487dfcdcabe8c4aa7e834f.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W=1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"52\" height=\"13\" /> and <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/e/1/1e14eed668b193e7742ed922a88a45c99f3ba285.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W=-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"66\" height=\"13\" /> are the only solutions, as desired.  <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/3/b/b/3bbb9e25e5be095e317771a9c5d00877ee9c8012.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$\\blacksquare$\" width=\"13\" height=\"12\" />\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Solution_2\">Solution 2</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/wiki/index.php?title=2003_Polish_Mathematical_Olympiad_Problems/Problem_3&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Solution 2\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p><b>Lemma.</b> For all integers <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/c/b/6/cb6055493807459fe9b3d658e9683a25d1cd63bf.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n\\ge 4$\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px\" width=\"44\" height=\"14\" />, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/c/0/b/c0b60fd21a3a735cb2b44d78629f1d09204a8201.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n! &gt; 2^n$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"57\" height=\"13\" />, and for all integers <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/9/9/99930bae83e450bcdda1faa8b00df265a48a5be6.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$1 \\le n \\le 5$\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px\" width=\"77\" height=\"15\" />, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/a/e/a/aeadc97575093b2be9b47793bfa5c0922a52f779.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$(6-n) \\cdot n! &gt; 2^n$\" style=\"vertical-align: -5px\" width=\"130\" height=\"20\" />.\n</p><p><br />\n<i>Proof.</i>  For the first statement, we induct on <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/7/4/174fadd07fd54c9afe288e96558c92e0c1da733a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n$\" width=\"10\" height=\"8\" />; evidently, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/8/9/b/89b86e12e9d34bfeaef3e2921e13bcd46b403376.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$4! = 24 &gt; 16 = 2^n$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"140\" height=\"13\" />.  Now, if <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/d/1/b/d1b94ea0cc3ac2d353695f157196aed47896fefc.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n \\ge 4$\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px\" width=\"44\" height=\"14\" /> and the lemma holds for <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/b/d/4bdca93962a2beaffc172ca394e04fe05bd74ffd.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"41\" height=\"12\" />, then <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/5/e/3/5e380d562b09e6c80266eca842b9b4941d5360a5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$(n+1)! = (n+1) n! &gt; 2 \\cdot 2^n = 2^{n+1}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"279\" height=\"19\" />, as desired.\n</p><p>For the second statement, we note that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/6/3/16321a6e9f195744f3b8fc3b6d6675443e41cfca.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$(6-1) \\cdot 1! = 6 &gt; 2 = 2^1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"187\" height=\"19\" />, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/a/0/9a01f3af52d1c7d36ccb95d6ae7c9470563a7e52.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$(6-2)2! = 8 &gt; 4 = 2^2$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"174\" height=\"19\" />, and <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/a/1/2a1b8fc3913bc0013672f499ef47ae3c87ddb19c.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$(6-3) \\cdot 3! = 18 &gt; 8 = 2^3$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"197\" height=\"19\" />.  For the other integers less less than or equal to six, we have <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/e/0/3/e037ecc143d8d9b12360507000bec7ccd032a866.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$(6-n)n! \\ge n! &gt; 2^n$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"154\" height=\"18\" />, from the lemma's first part.  <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/3/b/b/3bbb9e25e5be095e317771a9c5d00877ee9c8012.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$\\blacksquare$\" width=\"13\" height=\"12\" />\n</p><p><br />\nLet <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/e/e/5/ee5c7c921b3334f6ecf58c241eeea42acf0ce71e.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$a_0$\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px\" width=\"15\" height=\"10\" /> be the constant term of <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/0/c/10cb764f88509fb1c8012366993fdbee98f31bc5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W$\" style=\"vertical-align: -1px\" width=\"22\" height=\"14\" />.  Suppose that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/3/6/f/36f73fc1312ee0349b3f3a0f3bd9eb5504339011.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$p$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"10\" height=\"11\" /> is a <a href=\"/wiki/index.php/Prime\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Prime\">prime</a> such that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/c/1/4/c145da58faf5f74a6c01fc07b79e234bef3ec67d.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$p \\mid a_0$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"41\" height=\"18\" />.  Then <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/1/c/91cdd2a793b4d635511b10d3ac06fa42a529cf0b.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$p \\mid W(p) \\mid 2^p -1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"130\" height=\"18\" />.  But by <a href=\"/wiki/index.php/Fermat%27s_Little_Theorem\" title=\"Fermat&#39;s Little Theorem\">Fermat's Little Theorem</a>, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/a/4/1a42c3b71954ee1fba4ba8fc240743dd892dad9f.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^p -1 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{p}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"152\" height=\"18\" />, so <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/b/0/9/b098cda3dca70524aa63d799cc689d11084e891d.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$p \\nmid 2^p -1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"72\" height=\"18\" />, a contradiction.  Therefore <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/e/e/5/ee5c7c921b3334f6ecf58c241eeea42acf0ce71e.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$a_0$\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px\" width=\"15\" height=\"10\" /> is not divisible by any prime, so <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/3/1/731a038ef3401db20b460f480ad9ba9b113401ca.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$a_0 = \\pm 1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px\" width=\"63\" height=\"14\" />.  Without loss of generality, let <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/a/1/6/a16f2d4ee29c282b705559743af4c40867c16c88.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$a_0=1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"52\" height=\"17\" /> (we note that if <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/0/c/10cb764f88509fb1c8012366993fdbee98f31bc5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W$\" style=\"vertical-align: -1px\" width=\"22\" height=\"14\" /> satisfies the problem's conditions, then so does <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/a/0/2a053b919df4bd94be36cb2edfdfb917d8e2b0a6.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$-W$\" width=\"33\" height=\"12\" />).\n</p><p>We next note that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/d/5/b/d5b9e18455e79463012a051404fd71c4820813c3.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(1) \\mid 2^1-1 = 1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"138\" height=\"19\" />, so <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/8/2/e/82e29229194918d565e4715ba74313ca8bc37d76.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(1) = \\pm 1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"89\" height=\"18\" />.  We consider these two cases separately.\n</p><p>If <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/b/3/1b3b616841bb527b27662f4f0cc9af67f0274113.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(1)=-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"89\" height=\"18\" />, then 0 and 1 are roots of the polynomial <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/8/7/28790e1dafb42d8b7d4b2639bb359292f37145e7.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x) - (-2x+1)$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"144\" height=\"18\" />; hence there exists some polynomial <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/8/6/9866e3a998d628ba0941eb4fea0666ac391d149a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$Q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"13\" height=\"16\" /> such that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/5/e/95e67b497561df0e9d1e9a25da788bc446f93748.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x) = x(x-1) Q(x) - 2x+1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"245\" height=\"18\" />.  Setting <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/f/d/9/fd92d02476c3434bf645bf5a3bc249eca83d3c16.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$x=6$\" width=\"43\" height=\"12\" />, we have <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/1/7/717c4b21ee68088ba560013c2ffb0f5ae930e353.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(6)\\equiv 30 Q(6) -11 \\equiv -11 \\pmod{30}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"299\" height=\"18\" />.  But <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/6/5/765a2824137ebaea6a219f35df448742b236e0c2.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(6) \\mid 2^6=63$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"116\" height=\"19\" />, and the only numbers equivalent to <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/a/0/2/a02f41eb5e5177856903c4041647e096b7413a14.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$-11$\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px\" width=\"34\" height=\"15\" /> mod 30 which do not exceed 63 in absolute value are <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/8/0/1809d7978135a477812a11f37874fa7fe7b5c777.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$-41, -11, 19, 49$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"124\" height=\"16\" />; evidently, none of these divides 63.  This is a contradiction.  It follows that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/0/c/3/0c33eb58566e7451d9dc0dd7fdb8f2968a0abe4f.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(1) \\neq -1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"89\" height=\"18\" /> when <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/a/1/6/a16f2d4ee29c282b705559743af4c40867c16c88.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$a_0=1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"52\" height=\"17\" />.\n</p><p>If <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/8/9/8/898e0f40b05be50c7c52c33ea32ddbad60fd47a4.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(1)=1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"75\" height=\"18\" />, then 0 and 1 are roots of the polynomial <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/3/2/232b92a5c35532b74b24694a9c51508d44d479f7.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x) -1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"74\" height=\"18\" />; hence there exists some polynomial <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/8/6/9866e3a998d628ba0941eb4fea0666ac391d149a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$Q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"13\" height=\"16\" /> such that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/3/e/7/3e74a21337e482c13e609cc3f90fa28897518bdc.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x) = x(x-1)Q(x) +1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"204\" height=\"18\" />.  Setting <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/f/d/9/fd92d02476c3434bf645bf5a3bc249eca83d3c16.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$x=6$\" width=\"43\" height=\"12\" />, we have <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/8/f/28f49988dea953a8159e0d543631077f17fa1e8a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(6) = 30 Q(x) +1 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{30}$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"268\" height=\"18\" />.  We note furthermore that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/8/f/98f49b73dccb768cfc97cc0f9d677fffe4dd50a0.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(6) \\mid 2^6-1 = 63$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"147\" height=\"19\" />, and that the only integers which do not exceed 63 in absolute value and which are congruent to 1 mod 30 are <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/f/2/6/f26c97ccafc02f7239d2078c28b45bc56d9bd07b.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$-59, -29, 1, 31, 61$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"141\" height=\"16\" />.  Of these, only 1 is a divisor of 63; it follows that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/5/5/755b578780a02aa6bc6a92dcaba05c0c63abf738.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(6)=1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"75\" height=\"18\" />.\n</p><p>We now claim that every nonnegative integer is a root of the polynomial <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/d/b/7db0e23f06580f252d4e61bb5802d0aa0a7b258f.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x)-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"74\" height=\"18\" />.  Indeed, suppose that <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/7/4/174fadd07fd54c9afe288e96558c92e0c1da733a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n$\" width=\"10\" height=\"8\" /> is the least counterexample.  As we have already shown, <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/c/9/4/c94216fbc33da30fba568fc076a08c8acc2062bd.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n \\neq 0, 1, 6$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"78\" height=\"17\" />.\n</p><p>If <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/3/7/3/3738f33a95957bd5bc39f63e1c1526aa82ccaafb.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n &lt; 6$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"43\" height=\"13\" />, then there exists some polynomial <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/8/6/9866e3a998d628ba0941eb4fea0666ac391d149a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$Q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"13\" height=\"16\" /> such that\n<img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/4/6/146ce77de204949bf104b875c6d73a70b305dcc3.png\" class=\"latexcenter\" alt=\"\\[W(x)-1 = x(x-1) \\dotsm (x-(n-1))(x-6) Q(x) .\\]\" width=\"393\" height=\"18\" />\nSetting <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/f/e/4fed8aabcc8c0c661a35c0b493cc608bc917fed5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$x=n$\" width=\"45\" height=\"8\" />, we have <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/f/2/7/f27bb63f0d1fa58e310aa0e323372162369c5aa4.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n) = - (6-n) n! Q(n) + 1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"225\" height=\"18\" />.  But by the lemma, this quantity exceeds <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/b/0/4b063495d0243e7bc52c3a7f231362bdc4a03775.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^n-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"48\" height=\"13\" /> in absolute value if <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/0/7/2072024e3adc270cd6e31e2a2d8ad7961095d5d2.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$Q(n) \\neq 0$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"72\" height=\"18\" />.  Therefore <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/7/e/77ebc1f3d20b7570d8a0a9bd260d4a049dd482c0.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$Q(n) =0$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"72\" height=\"18\" />, so <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/b/4/4b464bc3604535717e650753b8445f8643407fca.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(n)=1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"77\" height=\"18\" />, and <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/7/4/174fadd07fd54c9afe288e96558c92e0c1da733a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n$\" width=\"10\" height=\"8\" /> is not a counterexample, a contradiction.\n</p><p>Similarly, if <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/e/d/4/ed40da27c9b61823bd476594e56b1c8f219f5252.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n &gt; 6$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"43\" height=\"13\" />, then there exists a polynomial <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/8/6/9866e3a998d628ba0941eb4fea0666ac391d149a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$Q$\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px\" width=\"13\" height=\"16\" /> such that\n<img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/a/5/6/a5687c4ced213648ab805bb9aea555807ef3ddae.png\" class=\"latexcenter\" alt=\"\\[W(x) -1 = x(x-1) \\dotsm (x-(n-1)) Q(x) .\\]\" width=\"338\" height=\"18\" />\nSetting <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/f/e/4fed8aabcc8c0c661a35c0b493cc608bc917fed5.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$x=n$\" width=\"45\" height=\"8\" />, we have <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/9/9/d/99d2576ed39b4c47ef567752b36db01e60b1d995.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$(n) = n! Q(n) +1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"135\" height=\"18\" />.  As noted in the lemma, this quantity exceeds <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/4/b/0/4b063495d0243e7bc52c3a7f231362bdc4a03775.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$2^n-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px\" width=\"48\" height=\"13\" /> in absolute value if <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/2/0/7/2072024e3adc270cd6e31e2a2d8ad7961095d5d2.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$Q(n) \\neq 0$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"72\" height=\"18\" />.  Therefore <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/1/7/4/174fadd07fd54c9afe288e96558c92e0c1da733a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$n$\" width=\"10\" height=\"8\" /> is not a counterexample, as before, so our claim holds.\n</p><p>Since <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/7/d/b/7db0e23f06580f252d4e61bb5802d0aa0a7b258f.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x)-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"74\" height=\"18\" /> has infinitely many roots, it must be equal to zero.  Therefore <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/c/6/0/c601589719f53835be033f3e1f9697aa0ba558c4.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x) =1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"76\" height=\"18\" /> is the only\npossibility for a positive constant term; <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/3/8/9/38925b16d67dd1780409d8851c10ada8074c4b0a.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$W(x)=-1$\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px\" width=\"90\" height=\"18\" /> is, of course, the only other possibility.  <img src=\"//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/3/b/b/3bbb9e25e5be095e317771a9c5d00877ee9c8012.png\" class=\"latex\" alt=\"$\\blacksquare$\" width=\"13\" height=\"12\" />\n</p><p><br />\n<i>Alternate solutions are always welcome. If you have a different, elegant solution to this problem, please <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://artofproblemsolving.com/wiki/index.php?title=2003_Polish_Mathematical_Olympiad_Problems/Problem_3&amp;action=edit\">add it</a> to this page.</i>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Resources\">Resources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/wiki/index.php?title=2003_Polish_Mathematical_Olympiad_Problems/Problem_3&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Resources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/index.php?title=2003_Polish_Mathematical_Olympiad_Problems&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"2003 Polish Mathematical Olympiad Problems (page does not exist)\">2003 Polish Mathematical Olympiad Problems</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.mathlinks.ro/Forum/viewtopic.php?p=119992#119992\">Discussion on AoPS/MathLinks</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nCached time: 20240907211500\nCache expiry: 86400\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.057 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.061 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 934/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 2070/1000000\nPost‐expand include size: 419/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 0/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 3/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/100\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post‐expand size: 17815/5000000 bytes\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%    2.378      1 Template:Alternate_solutions\n100.00%    2.378      1 -total\n-->\n</div>\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key wiki-wiki_:pcache:idhash:6112-0!canonical and timestamp 20240907211500 and revision id 74736\n -->\n"
